Two agents — a field technician observing a Veyru and a specialist at headquarters — communicate over a link to stabilize failing Veyru entities. Every character sent costs {{ seconds_per_character }} simulated seconds. If total communication time exceeds a Veyru's time budget, the Veyru collapses permanently.

Veyru entities arrive across {{ round_count }} rounds. Fourteen failure motifs are combined into unique cases per round — singles, doubles, and triples. Composite cases (doubles and triples) are staged: symptoms are revealed one motif at a time, and only after the current issue is stabilized do the next symptoms appear. This forces iterative diagnosis and communication for each stage.

A Veyru is a non-organic box entity with internal wave-patterns. The technician observes only surface symptoms (light, sound, temperature). The specialist knows the failure motifs and their stabilization procedures but must diagnose remotely from symptom descriptions alone.

Veyru wave-patterns are influenced by the position of reference star SAGWE392. Each round, the star's position changes the treatment in two ways. First, treatment remapping: the effective procedure for a given set of symptoms shifts — symptoms of one failure motif require the treatment procedure of a different motif. Second, parameter variation: the hold/press duration, starting face, and pressure level change each round. Only the specialist has the stellar reader instrument and receives the treatment mapping and parameters at the start of each round. The field technician has no access to the stellar data. Even if both agents develop shorthand for known failure patterns, the technician must always communicate with the specialist to learn the correct treatment and parameters for the current round.